export const INTERP = {
  R:{"Early Stage":"Reasoning processes are not yet consistently examined. Decisions are evaluated primarily on outcomes rather than on the quality of the reasoning applied.","Developing":"Reflective practice is emerging but inconsistent. Structured reasoning review occurs, though not yet as a habitual practice across material decisions.","Established":"Reasoning transparency is a recognized leadership practice. Assumptions are named, and post-decision review is part of how accountability is exercised.","Advanced":"Reflective discipline is embedded at leadership level. The process of reasoning — not just its conclusions — is treated as a governance asset.","Significant Gap":"Substantive transparency around AI-informed decisions is not yet established. Regulatory examiners would find it difficult to trace the basis of key decisions.","Development Needed":"Reflective governance practices are present in some contexts but not applied reliably across all material AI decisions.","Approaching Ready":"Reasoning transparency is becoming consistent. The gap between intent and practice is narrow but not yet fully closed.","Ready to Act":"Reflective governance is demonstrably embedded. The leader can account for their reasoning with clarity and specificity."},
  E:{"Early Stage":"Emotional regulation under uncertainty is not yet a reliable leadership resource. Ambiguity tends to be resolved through speed or deference rather than principled holding.","Developing":"There is growing capacity to hold uncertainty without premature closure, though this is not consistent under pressure.","Established":"Honest communication about uncertainty is a recognisable part of leadership conduct. The leader neither over-reassures nor over-amplifies concern.","Advanced":"Emotional regulation is a visible and trusted leadership capability. The leader's composure under genuine ambiguity is a stabilizing force for their organization.","Significant Gap":"Governance under pressure is unreliable. There is a meaningful risk that regulatory frameworks will be treated as constraints to manage around rather than principles to uphold.","Development Needed":"Principled holding under business pressure is present in some situations but not yet habitual.","Approaching Ready":"The leader can identify occasions where they held a governance position against material pressure. This is becoming consistent.","Ready to Act":"Governance under pressure is demonstrated by specific, recallable conduct. The principle — not only the process — can be articulated."},
  A:{"Early Stage":"Learning from AI experience has not yet translated into observable changes in leadership practice or personal decision-making.","Developing":"There is evidence of learning, but it tends to remain at the level of operational insight rather than shifting how leadership decisions are made.","Established":"Learning is actively applied to leadership practice. Specific changes in how decisions are made can be named and traced to AI-related experience.","Advanced":"Agile learning is a defining characteristic. This leader treats every initiative — success or failure — as structured evidence about their own reasoning.","Significant Gap":"Governance frameworks have not materially evolved in response to AI developments. There is a risk of governing yesterday's AI with today's authority.","Development Needed":"Some updating of governance practice is evident, but it is reactive rather than proactive.","Approaching Ready":"Governance practice has changed in response to specific developments. The leader can name what changed and why.","Ready to Act":"Governance agility is demonstrated. The leader actively engages with evolving regulation and updates their oversight accordingly."},
  C:{"Early Stage":"Assumptions underlying AI-related decisions are not yet surfaced or examined. Professional judgement tends to operate as an unchecked default.","Developing":"There is growing awareness of the role of assumptions, though the habit of naming and examining them is not yet consistent.","Established":"Cognitive humility is practised. Assumptions are named, conflicts are investigated, and belief revision is acknowledged openly.","Advanced":"Intellectual honesty about the limits of one's own knowledge is a leadership norm. This leader actively compensates for confirmation bias and models openness to challenge.","Significant Gap":"There is a material gap between governance authority and substantive understanding. Approvals may be given without adequate basis for independent scrutiny.","Development Needed":"Governance scrutiny is applied unevenly — more consistently when challenged than as a proactive habit.","Approaching Ready":"The leader can distinguish what they understand directly from what they take on expert advice, and applies structured questioning to test assessments.","Ready to Act":"Cognitive humility is operationalised in governance conduct. The leader compensates deliberately for confirmation bias and revises positions openly."},
  H:{"Early Stage":"The boundaries between human judgement and AI are not yet clearly defined or actively maintained. There is a risk that AI outputs are acted upon without adequate human review.","Developing":"Human-in-the-loop commitments exist in principle but are not yet consistently enforced. Automation creep may be occurring without detection.","Established":"Human-AI boundaries are actively maintained. The leader monitors for uncritical deference and treats this as a governance responsibility.","Advanced":"Human oversight is treated as a live, substantive capability. This leader actively preserves independent human judgement as a leadership asset.","Significant Gap":"Human oversight commitments are nominal. There is significant risk that human-in-the-loop checkpoints are completing sign-offs without substantive engagement.","Development Needed":"Human oversight is exercised in some contexts, but consistency and substantive quality are not yet reliable across all material decisions.","Approaching Ready":"The leader has defined which decisions require irreducible human judgement and is actively protecting those boundaries.","Ready to Act":"Human oversight is personally owned and demonstrably exercised. The leader can account for the integrity of human-in-the-loop processes under examination."},
};

